  </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> Starting:<br />
<br />
Aragorn no more no less. I always bid zero. I play East Gate to make the opponent pay if he forces me to go first. This deck was made to choke the life out of any Shadow deck while swiftly moving to site 9. <br />
<br />
Free Peoples: <br />
<br />
This deck is the mother of all choke decks. The vast majority of the time I see one maybe (big maybe) two minions at any site except 9 and by then its a done deal. This is a lay out of the twilight range from best case (don&#39;t get confused cause this is actually the norm) to absolute worst case for each site. NOTE: THE WORST CASE NUMBER IS THEORY. MOST OF THE HIGHER NUMBERS ARE QUITE IMPOSSIBLE FOR THIS DECK TO ATTAIN. <br />
<br />
Site 2: 3-4 <br />
Site 3: 2-6 <br />
Site 4: 3-11 <br />
Site 5: 7-8 <br />
Site 6: 4-13 <br />
Site 7: 7-8 <br />
Site 8: 5-19 <br />
Site 9: 9-10 <br />
<br />
Sites 1 through 4 are usually a breeze (I have never seen that 11 twilight, its purely theory). Wasting your stealth cards here is usually not needed (once had to use one to quite a Nazgul). If your opponent went first then you should be on site 4 first turn. If you go first and his sites won&#39;t let you. It&#39;s no big deal because your already in the lead. <br />
<br />
Site 5: Beware! There is no avoiding it, site 5 gives the opponent a bare minimum of 7, so watch for a Goblin Runner and Cave Troll (Worst fight ever, he plays a runner, the keyward, and the troll, I survived but had to stop at 5 and then 6, only time I&#39;ve ever had to do that). Thrarin and stealth events are key here. I also usually save Vengeance for here cause cave troll at six too sucks. Note that since your there on turn two and the opponent hasn&#39;t been able to empty his hand much (to dangerous to do so against my shadow, impossible with my fellowship), the Cave Troll is in fact a rare event period. <br />
<br />
Site 6: Unless the dreaded Cave Troll Popped up, you should be here at the end of turn two... well not always, but more often then not. Always rest here, even if some strange event gives you the chance to skip it. No real threat of a Cave Troll here, maybe a Witch King... maybe (never happened yet due to An Able Guide or them deploying at 5), but that wouldn&#39;t be too much of a problem. <br />
<br />
Sites 7-8: Suprisingly this area is not really that bad for this deck. Occasionly I&#39;ve had to rangers versatily and power according at one of these sites but otherwise no big problems. <br />
<br />
Site 9:  Times have proven to me that this is the site of bane for any deck, no way around it. It has high twilight and aweful site text for you. The Shadow turn before you move here try and empty your hand the best you can. If you have them and they have not been used as replacements yet, deploy Boromir and Sam. They and Swordarm of the white tower will likely be your big help here (well actually all 4 times I was put in this scenario it turned out different once it was due to Bounder and Sting, once it was just a bad draw for him, Once it was Rangers versatility and PATHS). <br />
<br />
Card Explainations: <br />
<br />
In deploying cards be very stingy, I usually don&#39;t deploy Sting or Rangers sword unless I have No Stranger to Shadows as well. Armor and Bounder always comes down immediately from hand because they are important. Healing is okay as you have the Gaffer, one Sam heal, one boromir heal, and three athelas if they&#39;re not needed for conditions. Plus sanctuary. Boromir stays in hand when you draw him until site 9 or Aragorn dies. Sam usually stays in hand (I&#8217;ve never played him) till late or until you get ATFNBS. They are strickly a pitch hitters and are normally not needed. They were added to counter direct damage decks that could kill Aragorn around site 5. Sting is huge against your biggest foe, the Moria and Sauron Orcs. Thrarin is a cheap road block and works as good as a stealth event I know. Isildur&#39;s Bane helps in those situations The Ruling can&#39;t and and +1 vitality is nice and sense it is usually needed at all the two burden thing is okay. <br />
<br />
Shadow:<br />
<br />
This is your basic swarm and plow strategy. With the exception of the Troll all your guys are cheap and some are free or better yet add to the pool. The key is to lay down everything you can every turn, even if it is just going to be beaten by the opponent or do very little damage. You want to empty your hand of villains and load up for your next free peoples turn. Don&#8217;t be mistaken. You will win a lot of fights and with swarms and host of thousands bringing down both your lost and victorious legions on your opponent it will get ugly for them really fast.  I play 3 Trolls because with my recycle factor I hope to get him before site 5 where he can easily hit the table. I don&#8217;t play the keyward because he isn&#8217;t worth it alone and most the time you never have him and the troll by 5. I of course use the common Host/Scavenger/Sword/Draw combo. Archers and wallcrawlers are excellent together and wallcrawlers are 8&#8217;s at sites 4 and 5.  <br />
<br />
Just play hard on this side and you&#8217;ll do fine&#8230; remember your goal is to slow them down and prepare you free peoples side&#8230; killing them is just and added treat.<br />
